===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|weaponry}} A long-bladed [[weapon]] having a handle and sometimes a [[hilt]] and designed to stab, [[hew]], or [[slice]] and cut. <!-- This is encyclopedic: It was sheathed in a [[scabbard]]. It was originally a [[melée]] weapon that was used in serious combat, but now is mostly used in sports and for ceremonies, and is viewed as one of the most noble weapons.-->
#* '''1591''', William Shakespeare, ''Henry VI'', Part III, Act II, Scene II, line 59.
#*: [[unsheathe|Unsheathe]] your [[sword]] and [[dub]] him [[presently]].
#* '''1786''', Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 49.
#*: Some [[sword]]s were also made [[solely]] to [[thrust]], and some only to [[cut]]; others were [[equally]] [[adapt]]ed for both.
# Someone [[paid]] to [[handle]] a sword.
# {{lb|en|tarot}} A [[suit]] in the minor [[arcana]] in [[tarot]].
# {{lb|en|tarot}} A [[card]] of this suit.
# {{lb|en|weaving}} One of the end bars by which the [[lay]] of a [[hand]] [[loom]] is suspended.
# {{lb|en|heraldiccharge}} The weapon, often used as a [[heraldry|heraldic]] charge.

